uarter of the 20th century. Through essays that provide a wealth of data on the courts and the legal profession in these countries, the book attempts to relate changes in the operation of the legal systems to changes in the political and social history of the societies in which they are embedded. The details vary, in accordance with the particular history and structure of the countries, but there are also key commonalities that run through all of the stories: democratization, globalization, and changes in the legal order that seem to be worldwide; more power to courts; a growing legal profession; and the entry of women into what was once a masculine club.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 4aLatin American Studies. 4aLaw -- International and Comparative Law. 7aLAW / International.2bisacsh1 aBergoglio, María Inés, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoigeol, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBotelho Junqueira, Eliane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCassese, Sabino, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClark, David S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDezalay, Yves, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFix-Fierro, Hector, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFriedman, Lawrence M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFriedman, Lawrence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFuenzalida Faivovich, Edmundo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarcía-Villegas, Mauricio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarth, Bryant, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rela